Turkish Equity Movers: Afyon, Banvit, Bimeks, Klimasan, Migros

-- B y   B e n j a m i n   H a r v e y
-- 
2011-04-14T15:22:32Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-30/turkish-equity-movers-ayen-anadolu-efes-bim-rhea-thy-move.html
Turkey’s benchmark  ISE National 100
Index (XU100)  fell 243.93, or 0.4 percent, to 67,959.5 at the 5:30 p.m.
close in Istanbul.  The following stocks were active. Symbols are in
parentheses.  Adana Cimento Sanayii TAS (ADANA)  , a cement producer,
lost 6 kurus, or 1.1 percent, to 5.6 liras after being cut to
“neutral” from “overweight” at HSBC Bank Plc.  Afyon Cimento Sanayi TAS (AFYON)  , another cement
producer, gained as much as 11 liras, or 6.2 percent, before
paring its advance to 0.3 percent at 179.50 liras.  Haci Omer
Sabanci Holding AS (SAHOL)  , Turkey’s second-largest group of
companies, might buy Afyon, CNBC-e reported. Sabanci fell 12
kurus, or 1.5 percent, to 7.8 liras.  Banvit Bandirma Vitaminli Yem Sanayii AS (BANVT TI), a
chicken producer, rose as much as 4.5 percent before paring its
gain to 0.8 percent, advancing 4 kurus to 4.98 liras. Seker
Pilic & Yem Sanayii Ticaret AS (SKPLC TI), another chicken
producer, closed up 13 kurus, or 3.4 percent, at 3.98 liras, its
highest since January 6. The two companies were among those
visited by a Saudi Arabian delegation as the country looks to
restart chicken imports banned since  Turkey ’s 2005 bird flu
outbreak, according to a report in Zaman newspaper.  Bimeks Bilgi Islem & Dis Ticaret AS (BMEKS TI), a consumer
electronics retailer, jumped as much as 45 kurus, or 10 percent,
to 4.95 liras before closing up 0.7 percent at 4.53 liras on its
first day of trading on the exchange after an initial public
offering. Demand in the IPO exceeded the 19 million shares sold
by almost nine times, broker Bizim Menkul Degerler AS, which was
hired for the IPO, said on April 11.  Klimasan Klima Sanayi & Ticaret AS (KLMSN TI), a
manufacturer of deep freezers and refrigerators, surged to a
record high of 4.33 liras after saying first-quarter sales rose
115 percent on the quarter. The shares climbed 29 kurus, or 7.2
percent.  Migros Ticaret AS (MGROS)  , a supermarket chain, plunged
the most since August 2009, dropping 5.8 liras, or 18.5 percent,
to a one-year low of 25.5 liras. The 17.4 percent stake being
sold by London-based BC Partners Holding Ltd. for 25 liras per
share will be added to the grocer’s free float, Migros said.  To contact the reporter on this story:
